<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06009225 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06009225 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Wayne Hagerman; ... Lived in Indiana  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; FIRE; PREVENTION; PROFESSIONAL; DEATH; OBITUARY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Military rites have been conducted in Marion, Ind., for Wayne N. Hagerman, 56,a former San Jose firefighter and captain, who died of lung cancer Saturday athis home in Hammond, Ind.;    Mr. Hagerman was born in South Bend, Ind., andattended public schools there. He went to Ball State University in Munciebefore serving in the Army during the Korean War. He joined the San Jose FireDepartment in 1962.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  WAYNE HAGERMAN, S.J. FIREFIGHTER  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Obituaries  </MEMO><TEXT>     Mr. Hagerman worked at Station 18 with Al Montez, who is now a battalionchief. Montez remembered Mr. Hagerman as &quot;a good fireman who was especiallywell-liked because of his sense of humor.&quot;;    Montez also remembered going ondistance runs with Mr. Hagerman at a time &quot;when it wasn't in vogue yet.&quot;;   &quot;You know, there are guys you don't look forward to working with,&quot; saidanother former colleague, Mills Ridgeway, a Station 18 captain who retiredlast year. &quot;Wayne was not one of those. He was a real pleasure to work with.;   Since returning to Indiana, Mr. Hagerman worked in custodial administrationfor the public school district there, said his daughter, Cathy M. Avila of SanJose.;    She said her father was a &quot;regular for years and years&quot; at Manny'sCellar restaurant in San Jose. He flew last year to attend a farewell partythat marked the restaurant's closing, she said.;    Besides his daughter, Mr.Hagerman also is survived by two sons, Wayne N. Hagerman Jr. of San Jose andBrian Hagerman of Hammond; a sister, Shirle Kowalisyn, and his parents,Vernona and Carl Deering, all of Hammond.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910109  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  268  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, January 9, 199100009225,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>